**Example 1: Validating User Input**

Let's say you have a simple web form with a username and password field. You can use JavaScript to validate the user input before submitting the form. Here's an example using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript:
```html
<!-- index.html -->
<form id="login-form">
  <label for="username">Username:</label>
  <input type="text" id="username" name="username" required>
  <br>
  <label for="password">Password:</label>
  <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required>
  <br>
  <button type="submit">Login</button>
</form>
```

```javascript
// script.js
const form = document.getElementById('login-form');

form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  const username = document.getElementById('username').value;
  const password = document.getElementById('password').value;

  // Validate username and password
  if (username.length < 3 || password.length < 8) {
    alert('Invalid username or password');
    e.preventDefault();
  }
});
```
In this example, we're using JavaScript to validate the username and password before submitting the form. If the input is invalid, we display an alert message and prevent the form from submitting.

**Example 2: Token-based Validation**

Let's say you have a web form that allows users to submit a form with a CSRF token. You can use a library like jQuery to generate and validate the token. Here's an example using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript:
```html
<!-- index.html -->
<form id="submit-form">
  <label for="name">Name:</label>
  <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required>
  <br>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
```

```javascript
// script.js
const form = document.getElementById('submit-form');
const token = Math.random().toString(36).substr(2, 10);

// Generate CSRF token
form.innerHTML += `<input type="hidden" name="csrf_token" value="${token}">`;

// Validate CSRF token on form submission
form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  const csrfToken = document.getElementsByName('csrf_token')[0].value;
  const submittedToken = document.getElementsByName('csrf_token')[1].value;

  if (csrfToken !== submittedToken) {
    alert('Invalid CSRF token');
    e.preventDefault();
  }
});
```
In this example, we're generating a random CSRF token and storing it in a hidden input field. When the form is submitted, we validate the token by comparing it with the submitted token. If the tokens don't match, we display an alert message and prevent the form from submitting.

